answers_data.content:
You have here multiple inheritance where both base classes have virtual destructors. The pattern you see in <pre><code>dtor_derived_so</code></pre> is a so-called "non-virtual thunk", which adjusts <pre><code>this</code></pre> before calling the whole class destructor. Normally you should also see <pre><code>0xFFFFFFE0</code></pre> (offset to base) in the second dword before the secondary vtables. I was able to produce code and vtable layout very similar to your example with the following source code:
<pre><code>class A
{
  int a, b, c, d;
public:
  A() {};
  virtual ~A() {};
  virtual int f1() { return 0;};
};

class B
{
  int x;
public:
  virtual ~B() {};
};


class C: public A, B
{
public:
  virtual int f1() { return 2;};
};

class D: public C
{
public:
  virtual int f1() { return 3;};
};


int main()
{
 D d;
}
</code></pre>
For more info, see the Itanium C++ ABI, in particular 2.5 Virtual Table Layout.
